# Code Overview

How `tetris.cpp` is put together, top to bottom. It's one file, split into
a thin platform-specific layer and a shared game core that doesn't care
what OS it's running on.

## 1. Platform layer (`setupTerminal` / `restoreTerminal` / `processInput`)

Everything platform-specific is wrapped in `#ifdef _WIN32` / `#else`, so
the file compiles differently depending on OS but the game logic below it
never changes.

**Windows side:** turns on `ENABLE_VIRTUAL_TERMINAL_PROCESSING` via
`SetConsoleMode`, which tells the Windows console to understand ANSI
escape codes (colors, cursor movement) the same way a Linux/macOS
terminal does. Input is read with `_kbhit()` (is a key waiting?) and
`_getch()` (read it), both from `<conio.h>`.

**Linux/macOS side:** puts the terminal into "raw mode" with `termios` —
this turns off line buffering and character echo, so key presses are
available to the program the instant they happen instead of waiting for
Enter. `fcntl(..., O_NONBLOCK)` makes `read()` return immediately even if
no key was pressed, instead of freezing the game waiting for input.

Both sides restore the terminal to normal on exit (`restoreTerminal`,
registered with `std::atexit`) so closing the game doesn't leave your
terminal in a broken state.

## 2. Representing the pieces

```cpp
using Shape = std::array<std::array<int, 4>, 4>;
```

Each of the 7 tetrominoes is stored as a single 4×4 grid of 0s and 1s, in
its spawn orientation only — there's no hand-written table of "here's what
the T piece looks like in each of its 4 rotations." Instead, rotation is
computed:

```cpp
Shape rotateCW(const Shape& m) {
    Shape r{};
    for (int row = 0; row < 4; row++)
        for (int col = 0; col < 4; col++)
            r[col][3 - row] = m[row][col];
    return r;
}
```

This is the standard "rotate a matrix 90 degrees" formula: each cell
`(row, col)` moves to `(col, 3-row)`. Call it once and you get the next
rotation state, call it four times and you're back where you started.
Same trick works for all 7 shapes with zero piece-specific code.

## 3. The board and the falling piece

The board is `std::vector<std::vector<int>> board`, sized 20 rows × 10
columns. Each cell is either `-1` (empty) or a piece-type index `0`–`6`
(which also doubles as the index into the `COLOR` table for rendering).

The currently-falling piece is a separate `Piece` struct (its shape, and
its row/col position on the board) — it does **not** live inside `board`
until it locks in place. This keeps collision checking and rotation simple
since you're only ever testing the 4×4 piece grid against the board, not
hunting for which cells belong to the "live" piece.

## 4. Collision, locking, and clearing lines

`collides(shape, row, col)` checks every filled cell of a 4×4 shape
against the board: is it off the left/right edge, off the bottom, or
overlapping a cell that's already filled? This one function is reused for
every kind of movement check — moving sideways, dropping down, and
rotating all just call `collides` with different candidate positions and
back out if it returns true.

When a piece can't move down anymore, `lockPiece()` copies its cells into
the permanent `board` array. Then `clearLines()` scans from the bottom row
up, and any row with no `-1` cells gets erased and a blank row inserted at
the top — which is what makes the whole stack visually "fall" down to fill
the gap.

## 5. Piece spawning: the 7-bag randomizer

```cpp
int nextFromBag() {
    if (bag.empty()) {
        bag = {0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6};
        std::shuffle(bag.begin(), bag.end(), rng);
    }
    ...
}
```

Instead of picking a fully random piece every time (which can give you
brutal droughts — no I-piece for 20 pieces in a row), the game shuffles a
bag containing one of each of the 7 pieces and hands them out one at a
time. When the bag empties, it's refilled and reshuffled. This is the same
approach modern Tetris games use, and it's also why the game can always
show you the correct next piece — it just peeks at what's already sitting
in the bag.

## 6. Rendering

Every frame, `render()`:

1. Copies `board` into a temporary `view` grid and stamps the falling
   piece's cells on top of it — so the falling piece is drawn the exact
   same way as locked pieces, no separate drawing code needed.
2. Walks the grid row by row, printing two spaces with an ANSI background
   color (`\033[48;5;<n>m`) for each filled cell, or two blank spaces for
   empty ones.
3. Prints the sidebar (next piece, score, lines, level, controls) by
   checking `if (r == <some row number>)` as it goes — cheap and simple
   since the sidebar only has a handful of lines.
4. Instead of clearing the whole screen and redrawing (which flickers),
   it moves the cursor back to the top-left with `\033[H` and overwrites
   in place, using `\033[K` at the end of each line to erase any leftover
   characters from a longer previous frame.

## 7. The main loop

```cpp
while (running) {
    processInput(running);
    if (!gameOver) {
        // move the piece down once gravityMs has elapsed
        render();
    } else {
        renderGameOver();
    }
    std::this_thread::sleep_for(milliseconds(16));
}
```

The loop runs roughly 60 times a second (`sleep_for(16ms)`), checking for
input every iteration. Gravity is decoupled from the frame rate — it only
triggers a downward move once `gravityMs` has actually elapsed, using
`std::chrono::steady_clock` to track real time. `gravityMs` shrinks as
`level` increases (capped at a minimum of 100ms), which is what makes the
game speed up over time.

## Where to make changes

- **Board size:** change `COLS` / `ROWS` at the top.
- **Colors:** edit the `COLOR` array (values are 256-color ANSI codes).
- **Difficulty curve:** tweak the `gravityMs` formula in `main()`.
- **Scoring:** edit the `TABLE` array inside `clearLines()`.
- **Controls:** both `processInput` variants use plain `switch` statements
  — add a case to either one to add a new key.
